==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sock
<hw>Sock</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>soc</ets>, LL.
<ets>soccus</ets>, perhaps of Celtic origin.]</ety> <def>A
plowshare.</def> <rj><au>Edin. Encyc.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sock</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sock
<hw>Sock</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>sock</ets>, AS.
<ets>socc</ets>, fr. L. <ets>soccus</ets> a kind of low-heeled, light
shoe. Cf. <er>Sucket</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The shoe worn by
actors of comedy in ancient Greece and Rome, -- used as a symbol of
comedy, or of the comic drama, as distinguished from tragedy, which is
symbolized by the <contr>buskin</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Great Fletcher never treads in buskin here,⟦br⟧
Nor greater Jonson dares in <qex>socks</qex> appear.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A knit or woven covering for the foot and lower leg;
a stocking with a short leg.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A warm inner sole for a shoe.</def>
<rj><au>Simmonds.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sock</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sock
<hw>Sock</hw> <pr>(s⟦ocr⟧k)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Perh. shortened
fr. <ets>sockdolager</ets>.]</ety> <def>To hurl, drive, or strike
violently; -- often with <xex>it</xex> as an object.</def> <mark>[Prov.
or Vulgar]</mark> <rj><au>Kipling.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sock away</ent>⟦br⟧
